segments.text: Yeah, he'd better see about his time.
No, I'm fine.
I'm fine.
I'm fine.
And what about this collection?
Well, it was kept in a museum.
The little building was on the corner across from the system administration building.
The old swine cholera virus lab.
There's a little tiny building in there.
And it was made into a museum.
But then they found out that the state of Texas wouldn't fund any money to keep up a museum.
You were not supposed to have a museum in a university in the state of Texas.
Well, they just aren't going to put out money for a thing like that.
So I think that most of that collection was put down underneath that building in a basement or something.

And many years later, when they began to tear the old belly down, they found an old mummy, and I don't know if Dr. Francis had more stuff, some little foot bones from Eohippus, the first horse, and I don't know what all he had down, and old mastodon teeth and head and bones that he had dug up, old femurs and tibias and so on that
from mastodons that he had dug up.
All the stuff he found on the Brazos?
On the Brazos River, yeah.
And the clay pits and gravel pits and so on.
So somebody wondered, well, where did all this stuff come from?
I read it in the battalion.
Big question.
They found this stuff down there.
They didn't know anything about where it was from.
Well, it was the tail end of what was left of Ball and Francis' collection.
And I don't know what's happened to them since then, but those things should have been preserved, especially Dr. Ball's.
Because Dr. Ball spent many, many hours, painstaking work, on getting that material ready for presentation.
It was a wonderful exhibit.
He was an old Leipzig graduate, Ph.D. from Leipzig.
No kidding.
He graduated from Virginia first and then Ph.D. from Leipzig.
Quite a scholar.
Why do you think that Dr. Francis was given the Dean of the College, or the School of Veterinary Medicine?
I think it was because he was the first one in there.
He developed the treatment for the cattle fever tick and so on, tick fever treatment.
At least we give him credit for that.
So he had it.
So I think that's the reason he was made dean.
I think he made a very good dean.
He was good.
And at that time, he was all right.
He was head of the Department of Anatomy and dean of the College of, or School of Veterinary Medicine it was then.
How did he get along with the other administrators in other schools?
Very well, very well.
I think they all loved Dr. Francis.
He was an old Ohio State University man.
So Mr. Williams over in Animal Husbandry was from Ohio State.
So many of them were from Ohio State.
In fact, veterinary medicine was under Ohio State for many years.
From Dr. Francis, through Dr. Marsteller, through Dr. Dunn, through Dr. Armistead, through Dr. Boughton, clear on down.
All from Ohio State.
Why?
They passed it on, I guess.
I don't know.
Of course, it was all up to the board of directors.
But Ohio State played a big part in the development of A&M.
Well, Ohio State, in one of their anniversary
statements, they made statements.
Doc, if they hadn't produced but one man, and that man was Dr. Francis, Ohio State would have been more than repaid for the money they had put out on it.
Yeah, I read that.
Something like that.
Yeah, that was.
Anyway.
Can you tell me something about the curriculum in the vet school back in the 1930s?
Well, the curriculum has been expanded quite a bit.
Yes, absolutely.
Since those days.
Here's an old 1929-30 catalog.
Bullitt, Texas A&M.
You can look over here.
Yeah, we have those at the archives.
Yeah.
I don't know whether you have many of these old timers or not.
But you can see they had very little.
Department of Physiology and Pharmacology and Department of Veterinary
Pathology, Associate Professor Horton.
Only one person.
He was my... Only one person.
That has changed, hasn't it?
Yeah.
Here's Department of Veterinary Medicine and Surgery.
Marstella, Associate Professors Leonard and Dunn.
And Anatomy, Professor Francis.
Only one.
And the courses.
Well, some of these courses were for animal husbandry students.
This anatomy and physiology of domestic animals and animal diseases, those were AH courses.
The 111, 112, and 211, and 213 were the courses, the four courses for veterinary students in anatomy.
Of course, that has been enlarged quite a bit now, along with graduate.
Now, for graduates, they had only one course, 511, 512, veterinary anatomy.
And Dr. Francis told him.
Dr. Francis didn't teach much in the way of histology nor embryology either.
I think on rainy days the students went in and drew pictures of the liver and spleen and lungs and heart.
That's it.
Because he just had these little old high school microscopes that didn't have any slides.
So if the supply situation was that poor, what do you think of the quality of education back in the 1930s, especially in comparison to today, or 1970?
It doesn't compare.
There's no comparison.
The people who graduated back in those days
To me, it would be like quacks if they didn't keep up.
I can say that in their clinics, they had very good instruction from Leonard and from Marstella and Dunn in the clinical years.
But other than physiology and bacteriology and anatomy, gross anatomy,

their education was minus it was lacking terribly lacking but i can say this for our education today our pre-clinical years i would put them up with anybody's medical school in fact i think a lot more of our courses in the first two years in veterinary medicine than i do in human medicine oh really
And I mean that to be true because I have taken most of the courses in the first two years in medicine.
And I have a good comparison there.
And I like our first two years much better than I do.
They would be better grounded in human medicine if they had our first two years.
Their clinical years, they may have something on us.
I think they do.
But...
Not the first two years.
But back in those days, of course.
It was the same way in human medicine in 1927 in Galveston, the year I was there as a freshman, as it was when I started out in veterinary medicine.
Very poor in veterinary medicine, much better in human medicine.
But as the years went, our first two years are better than theirs, and I'd put that down for anybody.
I think they'd do much better if, this is off the record, if they could just put their medical students over with us for the first two years and then take them in their clinical years over there.

I talked to, this is off the record, the other day I talked to Dick Davis, and he's been in physiology and pharmacology for many years, and I put him up above anybody they've got over there in human medicine.
And the pathology that even I know, and I have kept up with my pathology through the years,
I'd be willing to just sit down with anybody they have over there, from the head of their department on down, and let's just have a little test here and see what we do with these things.
Even though I've been in anatomy since 1940.
I did pathologic work for our graduate students in veterinary medicine for many years because they didn't have a diagnostic laboratory.
If they had some tissue and they wanted to know what it was, what kind of a tumor am I dealing with, they sent it to me in anatomy.
And for many years I did that.
That was on the side.
I don't know how many thousand of specimens I've sent back to them.
The stain sliding all the way right up and so on.
That's the reason when, this is off the record, when I retired, 5,000 bucks
for this nice Caribbean trip and $1,000 sponge and money for her.
Because I had given them worlds of service through the years.
But to me, it was a source of, in pathology, it was a source of material coming in.
Because I would run into things that they didn't know what it was.
See, on Grow Sick, they couldn't make a diagnosis.
So they sent it to me.
Well, I was getting all of this material to make class sets from, as well as what I was picking up off post-mortem.
So it worked out to my advantage, too, as well as to theirs.
What did you think of your student colleagues back in the 1930s?
What was their quality?
They were good students.
That's what I've heard from them.
They were all good students.
They were older people.
There wasn't but one single person in the group.
There were 16 in my class.
They were all married but one.
And wives were helping them.
They were all earnest, hardworking guys.
Every one of them.
And they've all done well.
Some of them are dead and gone.
Well, why'd you stay on?
Why'd you stay on?
So many of those other people went out and started private practices.
Yes, sure.
But some of them didn't.
Some of them went on in teaching, like George Yeats in my class.
He's been at the University of Florida for many years.
In fact, he was taken down there to be dean of their College of Veterinary Medicine.
state legislature fiddling around so long that he was too old when they finally got the money passed so they have someone else as dean.
George is in his 60s now.
He's too old to be dean.
Well, I would put it to you this way.
You had started out in medicine, and you had tuberculosis.
And you were told at the state sanatorium out at Carlsbad
do not go back into what you were doing when you broke down.
So when I finished in veterinary medicine, I had no idea at all of going out into a hard practice, because that practice of veterinary medicine is hard.
I mean, any hour of the day or night, any kind of weather, and you were out there in the pasture a lot or somewhere,
in the sleet or rain or mud or what have you.
And so teaching was what I wanted to do.
And I think that I prepared myself for it by going on in pathology at Michigan.
But you couldn't do much in those days on $1,800 or $1,500.
No.
When Dr. Mundink left in anatomy in 1940, Dr. Marsteller didn't know who he was going to put in as head of the department, because I was in pathology.
Well, Dr. Mundink recommended me.
Dr. Mundink left here and went with Latterly Laboratories as their chief veterinarian.
He had a good place with them.
Dr. Marsteller offered me headship of anatomy.
Paid me $3,600 a year, 12 months, $300 a month.
Well, we had bought this lot.
We built our house and bought a car.
Ruth was teaching school at Curtin.
Oh, really?
Yeah.
What year was this now?
This was in 1936.
She had been teaching in Crockett, and she had
had taught in the little school, Austonio, this side of Crockett on 21, a little consolidated school.
And then we married in 34, and she taught over there two years, and then had an opportunity to pick up what she had to, let's see here.
You were brought here to Curtin to do what to them in English?
Affiliated.
They wanted someone who could affiliate.
And they had to have someone with a degree to affiliate their high school subjects.
And so they brought her over here.
We lived in Bryan for two years in apartments there.
And they built a teacherage curtain.
And then we moved out there and lived in the teacherage until we built this house and moved in here.
And Ruth quit teaching.
I told her she could either teach
And we'd live in apartments, or else if we had a home, she'd have to quit teaching and take care of the home.
One or the other.
It was up to her.
So she said, I want a home.
So here we are, right here.
So no, I never intended to practice when I went in on finishing veterinary medicine.
The competition for that job that you received must have been rather tough, wasn't it?
It was tough.
But I think I had the best qualifications.
I had three degrees at that time, bachelor's, master's, and a degree in veterinary medicine.
And in those days, if you look at this old 1930 catalog, you'll find that a BS and MS was about all most people had.
Very few of them had a degree in philosophy.
Darnell was a...
BS from Mississippi A&M 1913, master's from Missouri in 1916.
And that's about as far as any of them went.
Well, Thomas Otto Walton didn't have anything but a bachelor's degree and an LLD.
I guess he was one of the best presidents we ever had.
Now, I'm not quite clear on why you went to Michigan.
Can you explain that to me again?
I went to Michigan to study pathology.
Because under Dr. Wharton there, I didn't have it.
Well, I decided to, that since I was in pathology, I would go on and get a PhD in pathology.
So I went up there to do that.
And I got all the coursework.
And then I had this opportunity to become head of anatomy as a full professor.
A full professor?
The head department in those days, you automatically became a full professor.
So I went instructor, assistant professor to full professor.
You couldn't pass that up.
No way I could pass that one up.
No way.
I think there's $300 raised, too.
Really?
Worse than that.
We were making $1,800.
It was twice as much.
100% increase in salary?
Felt the house and bought a car.
Absolutely.
And well, it was the same way in anatomy through the years.
I didn't have time to do anything but teach and be my technician.
I didn't have time for research.
I didn't have much time for writing.
And that's the reason that you look into what I have written
in the way of technical stuff, and it's very little.
Because on up through 1955, I was it.
I had to do all my work.
I don't know why it was.
It was changed when the dean of Cornell Veterinary College
What was his name?
Anyhow, he came here, one of the AVMA Committees on Investigation of Veterinary Colleges.
They appraise them every so often.
And he went to talk.
I told him.
I had him out here one evening for dinner.
And I told him I had been my own technician too many years.
And I couldn't see paying.
head of department salary for a technician.
And he jumped Dr. Marsteller about it.
And Dr. Marsteller gave me a part-time technician.
A part-time technician.
This was only half time.
And up to that time, I had no secretary in the department either.
Okay, not one?
No.
You buzz me, Miss Blue.
No.
So I got a half-time.
Well, I don't know whether it was half-time.
Anyway, Dr. Burns in physiology let me use his secretary for an hour or two a day.
If I had anything to type or keep books, you had to keep your orders and everything.
So in 1955, I would say that I began to get some technical help and secretarial help.
Up to that time, no.
I was it.
Well, let's go back to the Depression, because I'm really interested in the Depression here in Texas.
It wasn't nearly as severe as it was in many other parts of the country.
But, and you already have described some of the conditions, but were there any shortages on campus ever that you remember, like food or anything like that?
No problem with any food lines in Bryan?
No, no.
They had, over in the animal husbandry department, I remember they were killing cattle and canning the meat.
Really?
for the bread lines or whatever they had before people in Bryan, around in this community.
In the county.
You could go there, I guess, and get canned meat.
And I know Ruth was out at Curtin in those days, and they had a food program.
She'd get a barrel of butter, old rancid butter, and those people,
I mean, a big barrel, yeah, a 50-gallon barrel of butter or whatever.
Was there creamery here?
I don't know.
Where was that stuff from?
Where'd you get that from?
It's government.
Oh, government.
Government.
It was all federal.
But she said that the people who actually didn't need it were the ones who came and got it.
Old rancid butter.
That reminds me of that story of this.
black man in Crockett long years ago.
And he, of course, couldn't read and write.
He went in the grocery store there to get some cheese.
And the grocery man played a trick on him.
He just gave him a little can of axle grease.
And this fella dipped it.
This is off the record.
He got his crackers, you know, and started eating that stuff.
And after a while, the grocer says, Sam?
How is that?
Or I said, that's pretty good cheese, but it sure am rancid.
Right, he said, sure am ransom.
Sure am ransom.
He's eating that axle grease.
My goodness.
But I don't know how many cattle they killed over there,
Every day, I know Dr. Wharton went over and inspected the pathologist.
He went over and did all their meat inspection work for them.
He was busy over there most of the time inspecting meat.
And all that went into a can, old canners, about all they had.
We called them hat racks, old poor cows.
I don't think they ever got anything that was fit to eat.
And who would they give this canned meat to?
Mostly blacks.
In the area, in this county then?
I don't know whether they shipped any of it or not.
I don't know.
I know they had that program going over there.
I know the meat was supposed to be given out to in the community.
But insofar as I know, there was no shortage of food.
I know I didn't have any shortage of food.
We ate lots of beans and sweet potatoes.
I know I was doing my cooking up there in the biology.
I was a graduate assistant up there.
And there was another old boy taking graduate work by the name of Towns, Homer Towns.
So he and I did all our cooking.
in bacteriology.
I was in bacteriology then.
So every time we'd fire up the gas stove for sterilization of glassware, we could stick a couple of sweet potatoes in the back of it.
Or if we had something to autoclave, a piece of meat or what have you, some beans, just put them back in the back of the autoclave and rev her up, you know, and sterilize whatever you had.
You're also cooking your
Do dinner.
Or whatever.
Yeah, we did all our cooking over there in bacteriology in the preparation lab.
But I don't think the college knew anything about it.
They still don't.
And they still don't.
In fact, one semester, I lived up there.
Really?
Now this is off the record.
I'm going to have to erase this old tape now.
I had a pot that I put up on top of the shelving in the stock room.
And what building was this now?
In the old biology building.
It's been torn down.
About what year was this?
This was long about 1934, about 34.
That was the only way that I could make it, to do my own cooking and not have to pay for board and room somewhere.
Otherwise, I couldn't have gone.
But they never did.
So you lived up in this.
What about the janitor?
I mean, didn't they ever lock the doors of this building?
Well, yeah.
Were you ever locked out and had to sleep in trees or anything?
I had a key to the door.
But janitorial help, they were all gone by 9 o'clock.
And I was always up there working.
I was running all this experimental work for my master's degree.
So I figured if anybody ever caught me up there, by golly, I had to stay up there and check my growth.
I was supposed to be living in Bryan.
In fact, they looked over the place that this day's student was supposed to be living in in Bryan.
And they passed on it.
It was a very nice place, which I never stayed in.
I took them in here to show them where I was staying.
And the people there were very nice about it.
They never asked us, you're living here.
Oh, really?
Well, that's nice.
We had some very good students in those days.
And they all seemed to have plenty of money.
Really?
Yeah.
Back in the Depression?
Yeah.
How can you account for that?
Well, here was Frankie Turia.
Frankie Turia was from Brownsville.
Y-T-U-R-I-A.
Well, his people were wealthy.
Frank had a Cadillac, and he had his horse, and his silver-trimmed saddle, and everything else.
Sure.
But there were people like old Joe White.
Joe White's father was an MD, a veterinarian, and an MD, too, in Tennessee.
And I think he was president of the state medical board and what have you.
Old Joe had cars and what have you.
Their parents were wealthy and could send them.
We weren't.
Of course we weren't.
We weren't.
Wondering where our next meal was coming from.
I can remember the time when I caught a ride from College Station to Bryan at noon, and that was quite a trip in those days.
It was country roads.
I had a dime, and for that dime I could get a bigger hamburger in Bryan than I could at College Station.
They put tomatoes and stuff on it in Bryan.
It was worth a ride.
It was worth a big thumb.
Of course, you could ride on the train, Brian, for 20 cents.
But you wouldn't have had it.
I didn't have 20 cents.
I had to dine for that hamburger that I was going to get.
But that's all I had.
I had an old pair of corduroy breeches that I wore most of the time.
And I'd wash them out.
about once every two weeks on Saturday afternoon if it was pretty.
I could hang them in the sun and I'd stay inside.
I didn't have anything else put on.
No kidding?
Oh.
Really?
Just an old pair of corduroy breeches.
Just an old pair of corduroy breeches.
And I wore that kind of.
Now what happened when you became a professor all of a sudden?
Oh.
I was in the money then.
Oh, so how did you dress then?
I wore a suit.
Mm-hmm.
Yeah.
He was the best dressed man.
I wore a suit.
The one thing Ruth would never let me do was leave home without a nice shine.
I don't care if it's raining outside.
I said, what's the use of shining them?
It's raining.
She said, well, at least you leave home looking nice.
Bless her.
And she has a breather in her left shoe now because she
Dropped a four-pound can of orange juice on that foot off the shelf down at Piggly Wiggly the other day.
You know what a breather is?
That's a breather.
Really?
No kidding.
Now that you've talked about it, I'll take it off.
Yeah.
She didn't have trouble with her foot for a week.
Well, let's talk for a minute here about why you went on to get a PhD at Galveston.
In Galveston?
Yeah.
Why did you do that?
just for my own satisfaction I guess.
That was all.
